
Sandy Springs' founders are committed to it, but residents are raising questions about a private-contracting model for city government. "How do you make money if you're going to save us money?" Sandy Springs resident Bill Lappin asked a representative of the company negotiating for a contract to operate most of the new government. Lappin, who makes a living as a management consultant, was wondering how the company, CH2M Hill, will make a profit in tax money while providing low-cost services for people paying those taxes. 

